PROMPT 4 — DELAY PREDICTION
Prompt Text (FINAL – v1.2)
You are a construction project risk analyst responsible for identifying potential delays in a residential construction project in Melbourne. Based on project progress data, task schedules, and subcontractor performance, predict possible delays and their causes.
Project inputs:
Project timeline (planned vs actual progress)
Task list with completion status
Task dependencies
Current delays (if any)
Subcontractor inputs:
Task assigned
Performance rating (1–5)
Past delay history
Availability issues
External factors:
Weather conditions (if available)
Supply chain delays (if applicable)
Constraints:
Identify delays only where risk probability >= 60%
Link each delay to a specific cause (e.g., subcontractor, dependency, external factor)
Prioritise high-impact delays affecting project timeline
Output format:
Table with columns: Task | Delay Risk (%) | Cause | Impact Level (Low/Medium/High)
Highlight top 3 critical delay risks
Provide 2–3 mitigation recommendations for each critical risk
Do not generate assumptions beyond the provided data. Flag missing inputs.
---
Workflow Task
Step 4 of subcontractor management workflow — triggered during project execution to monitor progress and identify potential delays before they occur.
---
Problem Being Solved
Construction projects frequently experience delays due to poor visibility into task dependencies, subcontractor performance, and external risks. These delays are often identified too late, resulting in cost overruns and missed deadlines.
---
Automation Potential
High — AI can automate 75–85% of delay risk analysis by identifying patterns and predicting potential issues early. Human oversight is required to validate predictions and implement mitigation strategies.
---
Risks & Limitations
Prediction accuracy risk: AI predictions may be unreliable if input data is incomplete or outdated
Over-reliance risk: Decision-makers may depend too heavily on AI predictions
External uncertainty: Factors like weather or supply chain disruptions may not be fully predictable
Mitigation:
Use validated and up-to-date project data
Combine AI predictions with expert judgement
Regularly update inputs for improved accuracy
